07:51.080 --> 07:55.120
people on the west coast would know about it right away.

07:55.120 --> 07:57.000
That's pretty impressive.

07:57.000 --> 07:59.320
The telephone, of course, is a network.

07:59.320 --> 08:03.480
You used to dial a number.

08:03.480 --> 08:08.680
It used to make sparks in the phone.

08:08.680 --> 08:12.520
That doesn't happen anymore, but you dial a number and somewhere some distant person

08:12.520 --> 08:13.520
answers.

08:13.520 --> 08:19.160
Courtless telephones, I was around long enough to remember when those came out.

08:19.160 --> 08:24.800
All of a sudden you didn't have to have the receiver connected with a wire anymore.

08:24.800 --> 08:28.200
It's a sort of network, right?

08:28.200 --> 08:34.280
Then we had Ethernet, which obviously has been around since, as I remember, somewhere

08:34.280 --> 08:35.280
in the 90s.

08:35.280 --> 08:40.360
Before that it was like token ring and a whole bunch of weird stuff on coax.

08:40.360 --> 08:45.240
Although you can still do Ethernet on coax, but you get the idea.

08:45.240 --> 08:48.400
Wireless networks, I remember when those came out, so all of a sudden now I didn't have

08:48.400 --> 08:51.240
to be tethered with a wire Ethernet.

08:51.240 --> 08:54.880
I could do it wirelessly.

